body:
Here's the thread with the discussion:
https://users.rust-lang.org/t/specifying-that-trait-should-be-object-safe-for-purpose-of-casting-to-object/11564

Specifically, the following error happens

```rust
trait Trait {
    fn method(&self) {
        // ERROR: the trait `std::marker::Sized` is not implemented for `Self`
        let _ = self as &Trait;
    }
}
```
[Playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?gist=07b7d16bb344262c589e714ffb184281&version=stable&backtrace=0)

It claims that `Self: Sized` is needed, but really, we are converting the *reference* `&Self` to `&Trait` which should work for both sized and unsized `Self`.

To prove this, one can create an intermediary `AsObj` trait that successfully does precisely this conversion.

```rust
trait Trait {
    fn method<'a>(&'a self) where &'a Self: AsObj {
        let _: &Trait = self.as_obj();
    }
}

trait AsObj {
    fn as_obj(&self) -> &Trait;
}

impl<'a, Type: Trait> AsObj for &'a Type {
    fn as_obj(&self) -> &Trait { *self }
}
```

[Playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?gist=ac0b3c331673a96f232f4ec23195d845&version=stable&backtrace=0)

As far as I can see, `AsObj` has *no additional information* over the original `self as &Trait` at compile time and is identically constrained. The only difference I can see is that `as_obj()` takes, effectively, a reference to a reference, but that should make no difference. In particular, `*&self as &Trait` in the original doesn't succeed either.

So what gives? Is this a bug in the compiler?
